'''Juan Manuel Márquez Méndez''' (August 23, 1973) is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] professional [[Boxing|boxer]]. He is the 3rd Mexican-born boxer (after [[Erik Morales]] and [[Jorge Arce]]) to become a four-division world champion, winning seven [[List of boxing quadruple champions|world titles in four different boxing weight classes]].&amp;lt;ref&amp;gt;{{cite news|title=Temas calientes del viernes|url=<a href="http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/nacion-espn/?cc=3888|accessdate=9">http://espndeportes.espn.go.com/nacion-espn/?cc=3888|accessdate=9</a> December 2012|newspaper=[[ESPN]]|date=7 December 2012|archiveurl=<a href="http://www.webcitation.org/6CmHHUYvO|archivedate=9">http://www.webcitation.org/6CmHHUYvO|archivedate=9</a> December 2012|deadurl=no|language=Spanish}}&amp;lt;/ref&amp;gt;

A natural counter puncher, Marquez is known for being a fast and highly technical fighter. He is also known for his three close fights against [[Manny Pacquiao]], and by winning their fourth fight by a stunning knockout in the sixth round. ''[[Ring Magazine]]'' currently ranks Márquez as the number three [[Ring Magazine pound for pound|pound-for-pound]] boxer in the world and number one in the junior welterweight division.&amp;lt;ref&amp;gt;<a href="http://ringtv.craveonline.com/ratings&amp;lt;/ref&amp;gt;">http://ringtv.craveonline.com/ratings&amp;lt;/ref&amp;gt;</a> He is considered by analysts to be among the greatest Mexican boxers of all-time.&amp;lt;ref&amp;gt;<a href="http://www.complex.com/sports/2011/05/the-10-greatest-mexican-boxers-of-all-time/juan-manuel-marquez&amp;lt;/ref&amp;gt;">http://www.complex.com/sports/2011/05/the-10-greatest-mexican-boxers-of-all-time/juan-manuel-marquez&amp;lt;/ref&amp;gt;</a><span style="color:blue;">&lt;/rev&gt;</span>
